      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Documented simulation workflow with independent technical review; boundary condition and loading inputs verified against F1717 protocol.",
      "rationale": "Simulation setup checklist completed by analyst and independently reviewed by senior engineer. Boundary conditions (fixed inferior block, load application at superior block centroid) and loading rate verified against ASTM F1717-15. No use errors identified in review."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model form",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Physics representation (contact, material nonlinearity, large deformation) justified relative to observed experimental failure modes and QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Nonlinear geometry (large deformation), bilinear isotropic hardening plasticity for Ti-6Al-4V ELI, and frictional contact (mu = 0.2) at screw-rod interface selected based on observed experimental behavior. Fretting and fatigue not modeled (static test only). Model form uncertainty estimated via comparison to ensemble of three independent FEA implementations (FDA, Ansys, DePuy Synthes); inter-model spread < 4% for all QoIs."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Model inputs",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Material properties and geometric inputs traceable to measurements; input uncertainty propagated through model and included in total uncertainty budget.",
      "rationale": "Elastic modulus, yield strength, and hardening modulus sourced from lot-specific coupon tensile testing (dataset nagaraja-material-properties-titanium-alloy-2025q3). Geometric dimensions from CMM measurements of production screws and rods. Input uncertainty propagated via Monte Carlo (N=1000 runs); contribution to total QoI uncertainty < 3%. Re-validation of material property dataset against the updated model revision is planned for Q2 2026 following availability of revised lot coupon data."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test samples",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test specimens confirmed to be production-representative; traceability documented; N sufficient for statistical comparison.",
      "rationale": "N=11 constructs assembled from production-lot screws and rods with full traceability to device history records. Specimen dimensions verified by CMM prior to testing. Sample size supports statistical comparison at 95% confidence interval per FDA-recognized statistical framework. Two independent laboratories used to assess inter-laboratory variability."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Test conditions",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 2,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Test conditions span the range of clinically relevant loading scenarios; environmental conditions controlled and documented.",
      "rationale": "Testing performed under a single load configuration (compression-bending per ASTM F1717 at 5 mm/min crosshead speed, ambient temperature). Clinical loading variability (patient weight, activity level, spinal level) not explored in this validation activity. This factor is below the required level; the gap is acknowledged and additional test conditions are planned for a future validation cycle. Accepted under the overall credibility assessment given that all other factors meet or exceed required levels."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Equivalency of input parameters",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Simulation inputs matched to experimental conditions; any discrepancies identified and their effect on QoIs assessed.",
      "rationale": "FEA boundary conditions, loading, and specimen geometry matched to experimental setup using as-measured CMM dimensions and test machine records. Torque applied to set screws in experiment (4 Nm) represented in FEA via pretension elements. Sensitivity analysis confirmed < 1.5% QoI sensitivity to ± 10% torque variation. No unresolved input equivalency discrepancies."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Output comparison",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Quantitative comparison metric applied; total uncertainty (simulation + experimental) propagated; E/uval < 1.96 for all primary QoIs.",
      "rationale": "Normalized error metric E/uval computed for stiffness (0.84), yield force (1.12), and force at 40 mm (0.61). All values below the pre-established threshold of 1.96. Percent differences (6.2%, 7.8%, 4.3%) all within the < 10% acceptance bound. Total uncertainty budget includes discretization error, input uncertainty, model form uncertainty, and experimental measurement uncertainty."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the quantities of interest",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "QoIs selected are directly linked to the clinical risk and COU decision; justification documented.",
      "rationale": "Construct stiffness, yield force, and force at 40 mm displacement are the three QoIs specified in ASTM F1717 and are directly linked to the risk of construct failure (fracture or permanent deformation leading to revision surgery). Selection of these QoIs is consistent with FDA guidance on spinal implant bench testing and with the COU decision (design acceptance for submission)."
    },
    {
      "factorStandard": "ASME-VV40-2018",
      "factorType": "Relevance of the validation activities to the COU",
      "type": "CredibilityFactor",
      "requiredLevel": 3,
      "achievedLevel": 3,
      "factorStatus": "assessed",
      "acceptanceCriteria": "Validation scenario matches COU geometry, loading, and intended use; any gaps between validation and COU conditions assessed.",
      "rationale": "Validation performed on production-representative 7.5 mm non-cannulated pedicle screw constructs under the same F1717 protocol as the COU. Geometry, material, and loading are directly representative of the COU. The single test condition gap (Test conditions factor, Gradation 2) is the only identified discrepancy between validation and COU conditions; its impact is bounded by the conservative acceptance criteria applied."
